INSERT INTO xword.words (word, word_len, definition, submitter) VALUES ("rock","4","A ___ is any naturally occurring  solid mass or aggregate of minerals or mineraloid matter. It is categorized by the minerals included, its chemical composition and the way in which it is formed. ___s are usually grouped into three main groups: igneous ___s, metamorphic ___s and sedimentary ___s. ___s form the Earth's outer solid layer, the crust.","wiki"),("lava","4","___ is molten rock . The solid rock resulting from subsequent cooling is also often described as ___.","wiki"),("wind","4","___ is the flow of gases on a large scale. On the surface of the Earth, ___ consists of the bulk movement of air. In outer space, solar ___ is the movement of gases or charged particles from the Sun through space, while planetary ___ is the outgassing of light chemical elements from a planet's atmosphere into space. ___s are commonly classified by their spatial scale, their speed, the types of forces that cause them, the regions in which they occur, and their effect. The strongest observed ___s on a planet in the Solar System occur on Neptune and Saturn. ___s have various aspects: velocity ; the density of the gas involved; energy content or ___ energy. ___ is also an important means of transportation for seeds and small birds; with time things can travel thousands of miles in the ___.","wiki"),("jade","4","___ refers to an ornamental mineral, mostly known for its green varieties. It can refer to either of two different minerals: nephrite, a silicate of calcium and magnesium, or ___ite, a silicate of sodium and aluminium.","wiki"),("ovoo","4","When traveling, it is custom to stop and circle an ___ three times, moving clockwise, in order to have a safer journey. Usually, rocks are picked up from the ground and added to the pile. Also, one may leave offerings in the form of sweets, money, milk, or vodka. If one is in a hurry while traveling and does not have time to stop at an ___, honking of the horn while passing by the ___ will suffice.","wiki"),("iron","4","In its metallic state, ___ is rare in the Earth's crust, limited to deposition by meteorites. ___ ores, by contrast, are among the most abundant in the Earth's crust, although extracting usable metal from them requires kilns or furnaces capable of reaching 1,500 °C  higher than what is enough to smelt copper. Humans started to master that process in Eurasia only about 2000 BCE, and the use of ___ tools and weapons began to displace copper alloys, in some regions, only around 1200 BCE. That event is considered the transition from the Bronze Age to the ___ Age. In the modern world, ___ alloys, such as steel, inox, cast ___ and special steels are by far the most common industrial metals, because of their mechanical properties and low cost.","wiki"),("coal","4","___ is a combustible black or brownish-black sedimentary rock, formed as rock strata called ___ seams. ___ is mostly carbon with variable amounts of other elements; chiefly hydrogen, sulfur, oxygen, and nitrogen.","wiki"),("salt","4","___ is a mineral consisting primarily of sodium chloride  of solids per liter of sea water, a salinity of 3.5%.","wiki"),("rain","4","The major cause of ___ production is moisture moving along three-dimensional zones of temperature and moisture contrasts known as weather fronts. If enough moisture and upward motion is present, precipitation falls from convective clouds  which can organize into narrow ___bands. In mountainous areas, heavy precipitation is possible where upslope flow is maximized within windward sides of the ter___ at elevation which forces moist air to condense and fall out as ___fall along the sides of mountains. On the leeward side of mountains, desert climates can exist due to the dry air caused by downslope flow which causes heating and drying of the air mass. The movement of the monsoon trough, or intertropical convergence zone, brings ___y seasons to savannah climes.","wiki"),("tuff","4","___ , also known as volcanic ___, is a type of rock made of volcanic ash ejected from a vent during a volcanic eruption. Following ejection and deposition, the ash is compacted into a solid rock in a process called consolidation.  ___ is sometimes erroneously called 'tufa', particularly when used as construction material, but geologically tufa is a limestone precipitated from groundwater.  Rock that contains greater than 50% ___ is considered ___aceous.","wiki"),("gale","4","A ___ is a strong wind, typically used as a descriptor in nautical contexts. The U.S. National Weather Service defines a ___ as 34–47 knots  of sustained surface winds. Forecasters typically issue ___ warnings when winds of this strength are expected.  In the United States, a ___ warning is specifically a maritime warning; the land-based equivalent in National Weather Service warning products is a wind advisory.","wiki"),("pass","4","A mountain ___ is a navigable route through a mountain range or over a ridge. Since many of the world's mountain ranges have presented formidable barriers to travel, ___es have played a key role in trade, war, and both human and animal migration throughout Earth's history. At lower elevations it may be called a hill ___. The highest vehicle-accessible ___ in the world appears to be Mana ___, located in the Himalayas on the border between India and Tibet, China.","wiki"),("alps","4","Series of lower mountain ranges run parallel to the main chain of the ___, including the French Pre___ in France and the Jura Mountains in Switzerland and France. The secondary chain of the ___ follows the watershed from the Mediterranean Sea to the Wienerwald, passing over many of the highest and most well-known peaks in the ___. From the Colle di Cadibona to Col de Tende it runs westwards, before turning to the northwest and then, near the Colle della Maddalena, to the north. Upon reaching the Swiss border, the line of the main chain heads approximately east-northeast, a heading it follows until its end near Vienna.","wiki"),("kite","4","A ___ is a tethered heavier-than-air craft with wing surfaces that react against the air to create lift and drag. A ___ consists of wings, tethers and anchors. ___s often have a bridle and tail to guide the face of the ___ so the wind can lift it.","wiki"),("mars","4","___ is seismically active, with InSight recording over 450 ___quakes and related events in 2019.","wiki"),("time","4","___ has long been an important subject of study in religion, philosophy, and science, but defining it in a manner applicable to all fields without circularity has consistently eluded scholars.","wiki"),("snow","4","___storms organize and develop by feeding on sources of atmospheric moisture and cold air. ___flakes nucleate around particles in the atmosphere by attracting supercooled water droplets, which freeze in hexagonal-shaped crystals. ___flakes take on a variety of shapes, basic among these are platelets, needles, columns and rime. As ___ accumulates into a ___pack, it may blow into drifts. Over time, accumulated ___ metamorphoses, by sintering, sublimation and freeze-thaw. Where the climate is cold enough for year-to-year accumulation, a glacier may form. Otherwise, ___ typically melts seasonally, causing runoff into streams and rivers and recharging groundwater.","wiki"),("life","4","___ is a characteristic that distinguishes physical entities that have biological processes, such as signaling and self-sustaining processes, from those that do not, either because such functions have ceased , or because they never had such functions and are classified as inanimate. Various forms of ___ exist, such as plants, animals, fungi, protists, archaea, and bacteria. Biology is the science concerned with the study of ___.","wiki"),("gold","4","___ is a chemical element with the symbol Au .","wiki"),("mana","4","In the 19th century, scholars compared ___ to similar concepts such as the orenda of the Iroquois Indians and theorized that ___ was a universal phenomenon that explained the origin of religions.","wiki"),("adze","4","An ___  is a cutting tool similar to an axe but with the cutting edge perpendicular to the handle rather than parallel. They have been used since the stone age. ___s are used for smoothing or carving wood in hand woodworking. Two basic forms of an ___ are the hand ___—a short handled tool swung with one hand—and the foot ___—a long handled tool capable of powerful swings using both hands, the cutting edge usually striking at foot or shin level. A similar, but blunt, tool used for digging in hard ground is called a mattock.","wiki"),("onyx","4","___ primarily refers to the parallel banded variety of the silicate mineral chalcedony. Agate and ___ are both varieties of layered chalcedony that differ only in the form of the bands: agate has curved bands and ___ has parallel bands. The colors of its bands range from black to almost every color. Commonly, specimens of ___ contain bands of black and/or white.","wiki"),("opal","4","There are two broad classes of ___: precious and common. Precious ___ displays play-of-color , common ___ does not.   The internal structure of precious ___ causes it to diffract light, resulting in play-of-color. Depending on the conditions in which it formed, ___ may be transparent, translucent or opaque and the background color may be white, black or nearly any color of the visual spectrum. Black ___ is considered to be the rarest, whereas white, gray and green are the most common.","wiki"),("ruby","4","A ___ is a pink to blood-red colored gemstone, a variety of the mineral corundum . Other varieties of gem-quality corundum are called sapphires. ___ is one of the traditional cardinal gems, together with amethyst, sapphire, emerald, and diamond. The word ___ comes from ruber, Latin for red. The color of a ___ is due to the element chromium.","wiki"),("hair","4","___work, or jewelry made of human ___, has appeared throughout the history of craft work, particularly those made to be used for private worship or mourning. From the Middle Ages through the early twentieth  century, memorial ___ jewelry remained common. ___, considered to be a remnant off the person it was cut from, also has often played a part in myths and legends; in a Swedish book of proverbs, one can read that “rings and bracelets of ___ increase love” , which circulated among his faithful supporters. Other famous people who owned ___ jewellery include Napoleon, Admiral Nelson, Queen Victoria and her large family, Christina Nilsson and Jenny Lind.","wiki"),("neon","4","___ is a chemical element with the symbol Ne and atomic number 10. It is a noble gas. ___ is a colorless, odorless, inert monatomic gas under standard conditions, with about two-thirds the density of air. It was discovered , meaning new. ___ is chemically inert, and no uncharged ___ compounds are known. The compounds of ___ currently known include ionic molecules, molecules held together by van der Waals forces and clathrates.","wiki"),("zinc","4","___ is a chemical element with the symbol Zn and atomic number 30. ___ is a slightly brittle metal at room temperature and has a blue-silvery appearance when oxidation is removed. It is the first element in group 12 of the periodic table. In some respects, ___ is chemically similar to magnesium: both elements exhibit only one normal oxidation state .","wiki"),("lead","4","___  and atomic number 82. It is a heavy metal that is denser than most common materials. ___ is soft and malleable, and also has a relatively low melting point. When freshly cut, ___ is silvery with a hint of blue; it tarnishes to a dull gray color when exposed to air. ___ has the highest atomic number of any stable element and three of its isotopes are endpoints of major nuclear decay chains of heavier elements.","wiki"),("rust","4","___ is an iron oxide, a usually red oxide formed by the reaction of iron and oxygen in the presence of water or air moisture. Several forms of ___ are distinguishable both visually and by spectroscopy, and form under different circumstances. ___ consists of hydrated iron.","wiki"),("moon","4","The usual English proper name for Earth's natural satellite is simply the ___, with a capital M.","wiki"),("dppe","4","1,2-Bis. It is a commonly used bidentate ligand in coordination chemistry. It is a white solid that is soluble in organic solvents.","wiki"),("aryl","4","In the context of organic molecules, ___ is any functional group or substituent derived from an aromatic ring, usually an aromatic hydrocarbon, such as phenyl and naphthyl. '___' is used for the sake of abbreviation or generalization, and 'Ar' is used as a placeholder for the ___ group in chemical structure diagrams.","wiki"),("slag","4","___ is the glass-like by-product left over after a desired metal has been separated  from its raw ore.  ___ is usually a mixture of metal oxides and silicon dioxide. However, ___s can contain metal sulfides and elemental metals.  While ___s are generally used to remove waste in metal smelting, they can also serve other purposes, such as assisting in the temperature control of the smelting, and minimizing any re-oxidation of the final liquid metal product before the molten metal is removed from the furnace and used to make solid metal. In some smelting processes, such as ilmenite smelting to produce titanium dioxide, the ___ is the valuable product instead of the metal.","wiki"),("road","4","A ___ is a thoroughfare, route, or way on land between two places that has been paved or otherwise improved to allow travel by foot or some form of conveyance, including a motor vehicle, cart, bicycle, or horse.","wiki"),("heme","4","___  is a coordination complex 'consisting of an iron ion coordinated to a porphyrin acting as a tetradentate ligand, and to one or two axial ligands.'","wiki"),("fish","4","___ are gill-bearing aquatic craniate animals that lack limbs with digits. They form a sister group to the tunicates, together forming the olfactores. Included in this definition are the living hag___, lampreys, and cartilaginous and bony ___ as well as various extinct related groups. Tetrapods emerged within lobe-finned ___es, so cladistically they are ___ as well. However, traditionally ___ are rendered paraphyletic by excluding the tetrapods  is considered a typological, but not a phylogenetic classification.","wiki"),("tofu","4","___, also known as bean curd, is a food prepared by coagulating soy milk and then pressing the resulting curds into solid white blocks of varying softness; it can be silken, soft, firm, or extra firm. Beyond these broad categories, there are many varieties of ___. It has a subtle flavor, so it can be used in savory and sweet dishes. It is often seasoned or marinated to suit the dish and its flavors, and due to its spongy texture it absorbs flavors well.","wiki"),("coma","4","A ___ is a deep state of prolonged unconsciousness in which a person cannot be awakened; fails to respond normally to painful stimuli, light, or sound; lacks a normal wake-sleep cycle; and does not initiate voluntary actions. ___s can be derived by natural causes, or can be medically induced.","wiki"),("peat","4","___ , is an accumulation of partially decayed vegetation or organic matter. It is unique to natural areas called ___lands, bogs, mires, moors, or muskegs.","wiki"),("fuel","4","A ___ is any material that can be made to react with other substances so that it releases  energy as heat energy or to be used for work. The concept was originally applied solely to those materials capable of releasing chemical energy but has since also been applied to other sources of heat energy such as nuclear energy .","wiki"),("urea","4","___ serves an important role in the metabolism of nitrogen-containing compounds by animals and is the main nitrogen-containing substance in the urine of mammals. It is a colorless, odorless solid, highly soluble in water, and practically non-toxic  and is an important raw material for the chemical industry.","wiki"),("egat","4","___ has been the target of several lawsuits brought by neighbours of several of its operations. The best known legal challenge took place in Mae Mo. Mae Mo is the site of a 2,400 MW lignite-fueled power plant run by ___.","wiki"),("char","4","___ is the solid material that remains after light gases  and tar have been driven out or released from a carbonaceous material during the initial stage of combustion, which is known as carbonization, ___ring, devolatilization or pyrolysis.","wiki"),("wave","4","___ power is the capture of energy of wind ___s to do useful work – for example, electricity generation, water desalination, or pumping water. A machine that exploits ___ power is a ___ energy converter .","wiki"),("rice","4","___ is the seed of the grass species Oryza glaberrima .","wiki"),("pork","4","___ is eaten both freshly cooked and preserved. Curing extends the shelf life of the ___ products. Ham, smoked ___, gammon, bacon and sausage are examples of preserved ___. Charcuterie is the branch of cooking devoted to prepared meat products, many from ___.","wiki"),("ions","4","An ion , the net charge of an ion is non-zero due to its total number of electrons being unequal to its total number of protons.  A cation is a positively charged ion, with more protons than electrons, while an anion is negatively charged, with more electrons than protons. Because of their opposite electric charges, cat___ and an___ attract each other and readily form ionic compounds.","wiki"),("kiln","4","A ___ is a thermally insulated chamber, a type of oven, that produces temperatures sufficient to complete some process, such as hardening, drying, or chemical changes.  ___s have been used for millennia to turn objects made from clay into pottery, tiles and bricks. Various industries use rotary ___s for pyroprocessing—to calcinate ores, to calcinate limestone to lime for cement, and to transform many other materials.","wiki"),("koku","4","The ___ ,","wiki"),("holy","4","Ocimum tenuiflorum , commonly known as ___ basil or tulsi, is an aromatic perennial plant in the family Lamiaceae. It is native to the Indian subcontinent and widespread as a cultivated plant throughout the Southeast Asian tropics.","wiki"),("dill","4","The word '___' and its close relatives are found in most of the Germanic languages; its ultimate origin is unknown.","wiki"),("hemp","4","___, or industrial ___, is a strain of the Cannabis sativa plant species that is grown specifically for the industrial uses of its derived products.","wiki"),("mint","4","Mentha . Hybridization occurs naturally where some species range overlap. Many hybrids and cultivars are known.","wiki"),("sage","4","Salvia officinalis  is a perennial, evergreen subshrub, with woody stems, grayish leaves, and blue to purplish flowers. It is a member of the mint family Lamiaceae and native to the Mediterranean region, though it has naturalized in many places throughout the world. It has a long history of medicinal and culinary use, and in modern times as an ornamental garden plant. The common name '___' is also used for a number of related and unrelated species.","wiki"),("star","4","Illicium verum is a medium-sized evergreen tree native to northeast Vietnam and southwest China. A spice commonly called ___ anise, ___anise, ___ anise seed, Chinese ___ anise, or badian that closely resembles anise in flavor is obtained from the ___-shaped pericarps of the fruit of I. verum which are harvested just before ripening. ___ anise oil is a highly fragrant oil used in cooking, perfumery, soaps, toothpastes, mouthwashes, and skin creams. About 90% of the world's ___ anise crop is used for extraction of shikimic acid, a chemical intermediate used in the synthesis of oseltamivir .","wiki"),("blue","4","Trigonella caerulea ","wiki"),("isni","4","The FAQ of the ___.org websites states 'An ___ is made up of 16 digits, the last character being a check character.'","wiki"),("hail","4","___ is a form of solid precipitation. It is distinct from ice pellets , though the two are often confused.","wiki"),("soil","4","___ is a mixture of organic matter, minerals, gases, liquids, and organisms that together support life. Earth's body of ___, called the pedosphere, has four important functions:","wiki"),("asia","4","___  constitute roughly 60% of the world's population.","wiki"),("land","4","___, sometimes referred to as dry ___, is the solid surface of Earth that is not permanently covered by water. The vast majority of human activity throughout history has occurred in ___ areas that support agriculture, habitat, and various natural resources. Some life forms  have developed from predecessor species that lived in bodies of water.","wiki"),("sand","4","___ mining is the extraction of ___, mainly through an open pit but sometimes mined from beaches and inland dunes or dredged from ocean and river beds. ___ is often used in manufacturing, for example as an abrasive or in concrete. It is also used on icy and snowy roads usually mixed with salt, to lower the melting point temperature, on the road surface. ___ can replace eroded coastline. Some uses require higher purity than others; for example ___ used in concrete must be free of seashell fragments.","wiki"),("peak","4","The concept of ___ minerals offers a useful model for representing the changing impacts associated with processing declining resource qualities in the lead up to, and following, ___ mineral production in a particular region within a certain time-frame.","wiki"),("food","4","Historically, humans secured ___ through two methods: hunting and gathering and agriculture, which gave modern humans a mainly omnivorous diet. Worldwide, humanity has created numerous cuisines and culinary arts, including a wide array of ingredients, herbs, spices, techniques, and dishes.","wiki"),("wood","4","___ is a porous and fibrous structural tissue found in the stems and roots of trees and other ___y plants. It is an organic material – a natural composite of cellulose fibers that are strong in tension and embedded in a matrix of lignin that resists compression. ___ is sometimes defined as only the secondary xylem in the stems of trees, In a living tree it performs a support function, enabling ___y plants to grow large or to stand up by themselves. It also conveys water and nutrients between the leaves, other growing tissues, and the roots. ___ may also refer to other plant materials with comparable properties, and to material engineered from ___, or ___ chips or fiber.","wiki"),("vent","4","At the mid-oceanic ridges, two tectonic plates diverge from one another as new oceanic crust is formed by the cooling and solidifying of hot molten rock. Because the crust is very thin at these ridges due to the pull of the tectonic plates, the release of pressure leads to adiabatic expansion  are evidence of this kind of volcanic activity. Where the mid-oceanic ridge is above sea-level, volcanic islands are formed; for example, Iceland.","wiki"),("tufa","4","___ is a variety of limestone formed when carbonate minerals precipitate out of ambient temperature water. Geothermally heated hot springs sometimes produce similar  travertine. ___, which is calcareous, should not be confused with tuff, a porous volcanic rock with a similar etymology that is sometimes also called '___'.","wiki"),("moai","4","___ /ˈmoʊ.aɪ/ .","wiki"),("rome","4","Public parks and nature reserves cover a large area in ___, and the city has one of the largest areas of green space among European capitals. The most notable part of this green space is represented by the large number of villas and landscaped gardens created by the Italian aristocracy. While most of the parks surrounding the villas were destroyed during the building boom of the late 19th century, some of them remain. The most notable of these are Villa Borghese, Villa Ada, and Villa Doria Pamphili. Villa Doria Pamphili is west of the Gianicolo hill comprising some 1.8 square kilometres . Nearby is the lush Villa Celimontana, close to the gardens surrounding the Baths of Caracalla. The Villa Borghese garden is the best known large green space in ___, with famous art galleries among its shaded walks. Overlooking Piazza del Popolo and the Spanish Steps are the gardens of Pincio and Villa Medici. Noteworthy is also the Pine wood of Castelfusano, near Ostia. ___ also has a number of regional parks of much more recent origin including the Pineto Regional Park and the Appian Way Regional Park. There are also nature reserves at Marcigliana and at Tenuta di Castelporziano.","wiki"),("muds","4","Mud is soil, loam, silt or clay mixed with water. It usually forms after rainfall or near water sources. Ancient mud deposits harden over geological time to form sedimentary rock such as shale or ___tone . When geological deposits of mud are formed in estuaries, the resultant layers are termed bay ___.","wiki"),("clay","4","___ is a finely-grained natural rock or soil material that combines one or more ___ minerals with possible traces of quartz  and organic matter. Geologic ___ deposits are mostly composed of phyllosilicate minerals containing variable amounts of water trapped in the mineral structure. ___s are plastic due to particle size and geometry as well as water content, and become hard, brittle and non–plastic upon drying or firing. Depending on the soil's content in which it is found, ___ can appear in various colours from white to dull grey or brown to deep orange-red.","wiki"),("acid","4","An ___ is a molecule or ion capable of donating a proton .","wiki"),("mull","4","There are also ferry links from Fionnphort on ___ to the neighbouring island of Iona and from Oska___ to Ulva. In past years there were direct sailings to Oban , and to Barra, Coll, and Tiree from Tobermory. During the summer there was also a sailing to Staffa and Iona from Oban that called at Tobermory.","wiki"),("maar","4","A ___ is a broad, low-relief volcanic crater caused by a phreatomagmatic eruption  deep; most ___s commonly fill with water to form natural lakes. Most ___s have low rims composed of a mixture of loose fragments of volcanic rocks and rocks torn from the walls of the diatreme.","wiki"),("fire","4","A wild___, wildland ___ or rural ___ is an uncontrolled ___ in an area of combustible vegetation occurring in rural areas.","wiki"),("lows","4","Thermal ___ form due to localized heating caused by greater sunshine over deserts and other land masses.  Since localized areas of warm air are less dense than their surroundings, this warmer air rises, which lowers atmospheric pressure near that portion of the Earth's surface.  Large-scale thermal ___ over continents help drive monsoon circulations.  Low-pressure areas can also form due to organized thunderstorm activity over warm water.  When this occurs over the tropics in concert with the Intertropical Convergence Zone, it is known as a monsoon trough.  Monsoon troughs reach their northerly extent in August and their southerly extent in February.  When a convective low acquires a well-hot circulation in the tropics it is termed a tropical cyclone. Tropical cyclones can form during any month of the year globally, but can occur in either the northern or southern hemisphere during December.","wiki"),("west","4","The ___ern United States  is the region comprising the ___ernmost states of the United States. As European settlement in the U.S. expanded ___ward through the centuries, the meaning of the term the ___ changed. Before about 1800, the crest of the Appalachian Mountains was seen as the ___ern frontier. The frontier moved ___ward and eventually the lands ___ of the Mississippi River were considered the ___.","wiki"),("ibex","4","An ___ , the ___ can live 20 years. Two closely related species of wild goats are not usually called ___: the markhor and the wild goat.","wiki"),("nile","4","The present ___ is at least the fifth river that has flowed north from the Ethiopian Highlands. Satellite imagery was used to identify dry watercourses in the desert to the west of the ___. A canyon, now filled by surface drift, represents an ancestral ___ called the Eo___ that flowed during the later Miocene . The Eo___ transported clastic sediments to the Mediterranean; several natural gas fields have been discovered within these sediments.","wiki"),("lyon","4","Other traditional local dishes include coq au vin; quenelle; gras double; salade ___naise  is a cheese spread/dip made of a base of fromage blanc, seasoned with chopped herbs, shallots, salt, pepper, olive oil and vinegar.","wiki"),("lent","4","The English word ___ is a shortened form of the Old English word lencten, meaning 'spring season', as its Dutch language cognate ___e  seems to be a derivative of *laŋgo- long ... and may possibly have reference to the lengthening of the days as characterizing the season of spring'. The origin of the -en element is less clear: it may simply be a suffix, or lencten may originally have been a compound of *laŋgo- 'long' and an otherwise little-attested word *-tino, meaning 'day'.","wiki"),("flag","4","The ___ of Italy ; is a tricolour featuring three equally sized vertical pales of green, white and red, with the green at the hoist side. Its current form has been in use since 18 June 1946 and was formally adopted on 1 January 1948.","wiki"),("east","4","All of the electric utilities in the ___ern Interconnection are electrically tied together during normal system conditions and operate at a synchronized frequency at an average of 60 Hz. The ___ern Interconnection reaches from Central Canada ___ward to the Atlantic coast .","wiki"),("goad","4","The ___ is a traditional farming implement, used to spur or guide livestock, usually oxen, which are pulling a plough or a cart; used also to round up cattle. It is a type of long stick with a pointed end, also known as the cattle prod.","wiki"),("agni","4","___ is mentioned in many minor Upanishad